** Idea  **
All LLM providers — no matter how different they look — follow the same core pattern:

You send:  [ { role: "system", content: "..." }, { role: "user", content: "..." } ]
You get:   { choices: [ { message: { content: "..." } } ] }

switching providers is trivial.

How LLM APIs Work
The Universal Message Pattern

At its core, interacting with a Large Language Model (LLM) is nothing more than structured messaging.

You can think of it as sending a message to an extremely capable assistant:

System Message → Defines behavior, role, and constraints
User Message → Contains the actual query or task
Assistant Message → The generated response from the model

This simple abstraction powers almost every modern LLM API.

End-to-End Data Flow

CLIENT APPLICATION              NETWORK LAYER               LLM SERVER
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

messages = [              ─────── HTTP POST ───────►   Model processes
  {                                                   input context
    role: "system",       ◄────── JSON RESPONSE ────   and generates
    content: "...",                                    completion
  },
  {
    role: "user",
    content: "..."
  }
]

Response Payload:
choices[0].message.content  → Final generated output

Message Schema
All major providers follow a consistent structure:

{
  "messages": [
    { "role": "system", "content": "You are a helpful assistant." },
    { "role": "user", "content": "Translate this to French: Hello" }
  ]
}

| Role      | Responsibility                   |
| --------- | -------------------------------- |
| system    | Sets behavior, tone, constraints |
| user      | Provides input query             |
| assistant | Generates response               |


**Why This Pattern Matters***

This abstraction enables:

Stateless communication (each request is self-contained)
Prompt engineering flexibility
Multi-turn conversations
Tool and function calling extensions

It effectively turns LLMs into programmable reasoning engines.

**Industry Standardization**

The message-based API format was popularized by OpenAI and has since become the de facto standard.

Today, most platforms expose OpenAI-compatible APIs, including:

Ollama
LM Studio
OpenRouter
